   <titles>
      <title>Preview: New Linear Transformations from Given Ones</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>Here we discuss three ways of generating a new linear transformation from given ones</para.body>
            </para>
            <ol type="1">
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The sum of two linear transformations <math>
                           <latex>L,T\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math> is again linear, and it is given by</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>L+T\from \RNr[n] \longrightarrow \RNr[m],\qquad (L+T)(\Vect{x}) := L(\Vect{x}) + T(\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math.display>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The scalar product of a linear transformation <math>
                           <latex>L\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex>
                        </math> by a number <math>
                           <latex>t\in \RNr</latex>
                        </math> is again linear, and it is given by</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>(tL)\from \RNr[n]\longrightarrow \RNr[m],\qquad (tL)(\Vect{x}) := t\cdot L(\Vect{x})</latex>
                  </math.display>
               </li>
               <li>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>The composition of linear transformations <math>
                           <latex>S</latex>
                        </math> and <math>
                           <latex>T</latex>
                        </math> with</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>\RNr[p] \overset{L}{\longrightarrow} \RNr[n] \overset{T}{\longrightarrow} \RNr[m]</latex>
                  </math.display>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>is again linear, and it is given by</para.body>
                  </para>
                  <math.display>
                     <latex>T\Comp S\from \RNr[p] \longrightarrow \RNr[m],\qquad T\Comp S(\Vect{x}) := T(S(\Vect{x}))</latex>
                  </math.display>
               </li>
            </ol>
            <para>
               <para.body>We will discuss these operations in detail later on.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
